Problems with using Lisp for posets
===================================

   Lisp is slower than Fortran and C, possibly because it is so flexible
   and high level.  There are optimizing compilers for most lisps which
   speed things up considerably (and potentially moreso when the types
   of the variables are `declared' to the compiler, as one is required
   to do in languages like C); however, in my experience, the code they
   produce is still nowhere near as fast as that produced by C or
   Fortran.  I suspect that speed will remain a serious problem until
   such time as more efficient lisp compilers are produced.

   The printed representation of lisp code is awkward, with virtually
   all grouping done by parentheses, in contrast to languages which
   utilize separating words like `then' and `else'.  However, the
   formatting facilities of editors like emacs make the visual parsing
   of multiple parentheses fairly painless.  

   In this package, I have also introduced and utilized some macros that
   help make the syntax clearer (see above).


Elisp versus Common Lisp
========================

   Emacs Lisp (elisp) is widely available since virtually all unix
     systems come with emacs; other lisps are not.

   Using the CL package distributed with emacs provides most of the
     common lisp functions which elisp lacks, but not having truly local
     function-parameters (variables with `lexical scope') is a major
     nuisance.


Lisp versus C
=============

   C has structures and pointers, so in principle it affords 
   the same possibilities as Lisp does for representing 
   posets naturally.
  
   Sets with dynamically changing sizes are possible in C, as 
   in Lisp.  A difference is that memory allocation is done
   automatically in Lisp, but controlled explicitly by the 
   programmer in C.

   C is not interactive, Lisp is.

   C is not as high level as Lisp.

   C lacks built-ins for dealing with sets.

   C code runs much faster than Lisp code.

